Method number() in JavaScript:
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<body>

<h2>JavaScript Global Methods</h2>

<p>The Number() method converts variables to numbers:</p>

<p id="demo"></p>

<script>
document.getElementById("demo").innerHTML = 
  Number(true) + "<br>" +
  Number(false) + "<br>" +
  Number("10") + "<br>" + 
  Number("  10") + "<br>" +
  Number("10  ") + "<br>" +
  Number(" 10  ") + "<br>" +
  Number("10.33") + "<br>" + 
  Number("10,33") + "<br>" +
  Number("10 33") + "<br>" +
  Number("John");
</script>

</body>

The output will be :
1
0
10
10
10
10
10.33
NaN
NaN
NaN

This method can recognize all the numbers and the basic true/false input, but not with strange separation like comma and char.
